                  <li><strong>DfT Highway Maintenance Block</strong> for Lancashire averaged just &pound;25M/year from 2013&ndash;2021, while LCC managed a &pound;10B asset base needing &pound;95&ndash;110M/year investment.</li>
                  <li><strong>&pound;715M spent on the Rwanda deportation scheme</strong> &mdash; zero involuntary deportations. That money alone would have cleared Lancashire&rsquo;s entire &pound;650M road backlog.</li>
                  <li><strong>HS2 absorbed &pound;40.5B</strong> and counting, while the national local road backlog grew to &pound;16.81B. The cancelled northern legs wasted &pound;2.6B alone.</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="spending-era-result">
                  <strong>Result for Lancashire:</strong> 14 years of cumulative underfunding created an &pound;834M investment shortfall. Only 39% of what roads needed was actually invested. 27.6% of residential roads now need structural maintenance &mdash; 10 points worse than the national average.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="spending-era">
              <div class="spending-era-header spending-era--lab">
                <span class="spending-era-years">2024&ndash;present</span>
                <span class="spending-era-party">Labour Government</span>
              </div>
              <div class="spending-era-body">
                <ul>
                  <li><strong>Foreign aid maintained</strong> at 0.5% of GNI (&pound;14.1B in 2024) &mdash; announced cut to 0.3% by 2027, but money redirected to defence, not roads.</li>
                  <li><strong>Asylum costs continuing</strong> at &pound;4.9B (2024/25 estimate, NAO). The hotel-dependency model persists. Processing backlogs remain.</li>
                  <li><strong>No step-change in local road funding</strong> &mdash; the 2025/26 DfT Highway Maintenance Block was &pound;1.6B for all of England. Lancashire&rsquo;s share: &pound;43M. The &pound;16.81B national backlog continues to grow.</li>
                  <li><strong>HS2 costs escalating</strong> &mdash; programme reset expected in 2026 with completion pushed to late 2030s. More money absorbed by a project most taxpayers will never use.</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="spending-era-result">
                  <strong>The pattern continues:</strong> Labour inherited a road crisis and chose to maintain foreign aid commitments and asylum spending levels rather than redirect funding to crumbling local infrastructure.
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="key-insight-box">
            <strong>The bottom line:</strong> Lancashire&rsquo;s &pound;650M road backlog &mdash; 14 years in the making &mdash; is less than the UK spends on asylum hotels in a single year (&pound;3B). It is less than 5% of what has been spent on HS2. It is equivalent to just 17 days of foreign aid spending. These were political choices, not inevitabilities.
          </div>
        </Accordion>

        <Accordion title="Reform UK: A Different Approach at County Level" defaultOpen={false}>
          <div class="spending-era-body">
            <p>Following the May 2025 local elections, Reform UK took control of Lancashire County Council with 53 of 84 seats. The 2026/27 budget represents the first Reform-controlled highways programme:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>&pound;72M capital programme</strong> &mdash; the highest in LCC&rsquo;s history. Up from &pound;54M the previous year.</li>
              <li><strong>&pound;45M additional borrowing</strong> approved for pothole repair over 3 years (&pound;15M/year).</li>
              <li><strong>New maintenance contract</strong> delivering 42% fewer defects, 3&times; larger repairs, and 50% lower unit costs.</li>
              <li><strong>DfT 4-year settlement secured:</strong> &pound;268M over 2026&ndash;2030, rising from &pound;55M to &pound;79.4M/year.</li>
            </ul>
            <p>At &pound;72M/year, the programme is still only 65% of the &pound;110M practical steady-state needed &mdash; but it represents a genuine step-change from the &pound;26&ndash;35M years of 2013&ndash;2020. The question is whether central government will match this local ambition with adequate DfT funding.</p>
          </div>
        </Accordion>

        <!-- Sources -->
        <p class="assets-sources">
          Sources: NAO <em>Investigation into Asylum Accommodation</em> HC 635 (Mar 2024) &bull; FCDO <em>Statistics on International Development 2024</em> &bull; House of Commons Library CBP-9975 (Apr 2025) &bull; Home Office <em>MEDP with Rwanda Associated Costs</em> (Dec 2024) &bull; DfT <em>HS2 6-monthly Report</em> (Jul 2025) &bull; DfT <em>Highway Maintenance Block Allocations</em> 2025/26 &amp; 2026&ndash;30 &bull; LCC Full Council Budget Feb 2026.
        </p>
      </ScrollReveal>
    </div>
  </section>

